WEBVTT

00:03.119 --> 00:07.485
And I was born here in Laredo, Webb County, Texas. 
My father is the late Mercury Martinez, who is

00:08.967 --> 00:20.103
originally from San Ignacio, Zapata County, 
Texas. And my mother came from the old town of

00:21.725 --> 00:29.316
Guerrero, Tamaulipas, Mexico. And her name was 
Cristina TreveÃ±o.

00:36.177 --> 00:39.403
You would like to have a little information about 
my father. About your father. All

00:40.324 --> 00:47.036
right. Yes, I'd like to know more about your 
father. Perhaps you could just begin with a short

00:50.101 --> 00:56.493
account of his life as you know it. Well, my 
father... was the son of Proceso Martinez, who

01:02.553 --> 01:31.362
married one of the original descendants of the 
original settlers of the old town of San Ignacio in

01:02.553 --> 01:31.362
Zapata County, Texas, by the name of Maria Jesus 
Uribe, who was the daughter of Don Jesus Uribe.

01:32.017 --> 01:35.441
My grandfather used to be a merchant. It is said 
that he was the one that originally introduced the

01:35.461 --> 01:49.860
plow and also the lantern into this South Texas 
area at that time by the fact that he was a merchant

01:35.461 --> 01:49.860
and brought in many of these things. Prior to that 
time, all they used were camels.

01:55.647 --> 02:01.855
My father was educated or received his... primary 
education in the old town of San Ignacio. And from

02:07.485 --> 02:23.569
there, and against the wishes of his father, Don 
Proceso, he decided that he was going to get his

02:07.485 --> 02:23.569
formal schooling by going to Austin, Texas and 
registering at St. Edward's University. Why did

02:24.130 --> 02:27.035
his father not want him to do that? Because at that 
time, they believed that They had more than enough

02:30.286 --> 02:31.988
work. They believed in the ranch life. And with the 
primary schooling that they had was more than

02:34.610 --> 02:38.333
enough. How many years was this? This was about 
eight, 10 years of actual schooling that he had

02:40.395 --> 02:46.260
received. So basically against the wishes of his 
father, but with the full support of a man that my

02:47.942 --> 02:59.112
father became very close to, and that was Mr. A.M. 
Bruni. And Mr. A.M. Bruni guaranteed his

03:06.224 --> 03:18.804
education, or at least if he needed any help, that 
he would make sure that he would provide him with

03:06.224 --> 03:18.804
the necessary funds, which he did. And I 
understand that after he got his education, my

03:19.065 --> 03:28.339
father was able to repay every penny that he 
borrowed from Juan Antonio at the time. But he

03:29.112 --> 03:40.483
decided to go to St. Edward's College, and he was 
able to get his what is referred to at that time as

03:29.112 --> 03:40.483
Master of Accounts degree. He graduated in 1898 
from St. Edward's College. From there, he came to

03:47.931 --> 03:57.060
San Ignacio, and he started teaching in the old 
settlement of Dolores in Zapata County. There he

03:57.935 --> 04:13.674
thought for about 10, 12 years, at which time he 
decided to get a little bit more involved in

03:57.935 --> 04:13.674
politics, and he ran for county treasurer, which 
he was elected. It was during this time, I

04:15.236 --> 04:26.389
understand, that the elections got so hot that my 
father had a prize on his head And they were gunning

04:27.263 --> 04:28.984
for him. Who was gunning for him? Well, some of the 
opposing candidates. What party did your father

04:35.290 --> 04:37.232
represent? Well, he represented the party that 
was being headed by the old judge, A.P. Spahn. And

04:45.939 --> 04:56.308
it got to the point that whenever he would go to bed, 
he would fix his bed in one corner, and after he

04:45.939 --> 04:56.308
would turn off the lamp, he would move his bed to the 
opposite corner just in case. And his horse was so

05:02.134 --> 05:06.678
well trained that it would follow him wherever he 
would go. And he used to relate one comment or one

05:08.140 --> 05:12.504
little story. He said one time this friend of his 
made a bet that if he would go through this

05:12.524 --> 05:24.657
particular house, that the horse wouldn't follow 
him. And he took him up on it. So he got off the horse

05:27.507 --> 05:35.504
and went into the main room, which was considered, 
you might say, the living room. The horse

05:35.824 --> 05:44.723
followed, went into the dining room, the horse 
followed, went into the kitchen, the horse

05:35.824 --> 05:44.723
followed, and on through the kitchen, and the 
horse was right behind him. That's how bad

05:45.361 --> 05:55.174
politics was at the time, and he just wanted to make 
sure that he had his method of transportation so

05:45.361 --> 05:55.174
he'd need to ride on all of a sudden. Where was he 
living during the election? Was he still in

05:57.316 --> 05:58.778
Dolores? He was in San Ignacio at the time. He had 
gone to San Ignacio. He had gone to San Ignacio. And

06:03.364 --> 06:10.393
after he got elected, of course, he went and lived 
in Zapata, the old town of Zapata. And he was there.

06:13.120 --> 06:36.370
for up until the time that he moved down here to 
Laredo, at which time he started working as an

06:13.120 --> 06:36.370
investigator and overall troubleshooter, 
including, I would say, bookkeeper, interpreter

06:13.120 --> 06:36.370
for the old law firm of Hicks, Hicks, Dixon, and 
Bobbitt. And this was in the 1920s, late 1920s.

06:43.765 --> 07:01.942
I think he still continued to have a very active 
role in the local politics, primarily in Zapata

06:43.765 --> 07:01.942
County, and he never really lost touch of it 
because people really respected him

06:43.765 --> 07:01.942
considerably. Probably I would imagine the 
reason why he loved politics so much is his father

07:02.943 --> 07:10.811
was a county commissioner for 30 years. That was 
Don Proceso. And then after Don Proceso retired,

07:13.280 --> 07:25.155
then his son, Proceso Jr., who was younger than my 
father, was elected county commissioner. And he

07:25.276 --> 07:29.561
was a county commissioner in Zapata for another 30 
years. So I guess this is part of the reason. The

07:33.246 --> 07:37.111
politics was in his blood, and he always lived it. 
But he related most interesting times So to go back

07:42.490 --> 07:48.816
to an earlier question, you said that A.M. Bruni 
helped him go through college. Now, how did your

07:48.876 --> 07:51.819
father get acquainted with A.M. Bruni? Well, when 
Don Antonio first came here from the old country,

07:53.380 --> 08:10.877
from Italy, my father used to buy quite a number of 
what we referred to as or skins for Mr. Bruni, who in

08:11.026 --> 08:16.552
turn, Mr. Bruni, would sell further up in the east. 
Were these cattle skins? Cattle skins and

08:18.173 --> 08:21.296
primarily cattle skins. And over the years, he was 
able to, and again, too, by the fact that my

08:22.838 --> 08:32.587
grandfather was a merchant in San Ignacio. He had a 
store in San Ignacio. This was also part of the

08:35.010 --> 08:40.155
friendship that developed over that period of 
time. And after my father got out or graduated from

08:41.266 --> 08:52.558
St. Edward's, this relationship continued. And 
on a number of occasions, as I mentioned to you a

08:53.719 --> 09:00.206
little earlier, my father was used. He was a 
go-between, you might say, to buy land for Tony

09:01.007 --> 09:06.953
Bruni. And this, of course, was done primarily to 
keep the original sellers or the original owners

09:07.861 --> 09:21.798
of the land from hiking the prices on that land. 
When they found that it was Bruni who was... Who was

09:21.818 --> 09:26.804
the one that was actually interested in buying the 
land. Yeah, well, tell the story about Bruni's

09:26.824 --> 09:30.088
land and their extent. Well, my father used to 
relate that Mr. Bruni had so much land that a man

09:30.541 --> 09:49.371
would start at the crack of daybreak, crack of 
dawn, ride on horseback, which was right on the

09:30.541 --> 09:49.371
edge of the river, and ride out all day long. And 
this would be hard riding on horseback. And it'd

09:52.900 --> 09:57.824
get dark, and he would still be riding on Bruny 
land. That's how much land A.M. Bruny had

09:57.865 --> 10:02.569
accumulated over his lifetime. As a matter of 
fact, when Mr. Bruny died,

10:03.510 --> 10:20.325
my father still had under his name, as you might say 
the owner, 5,000 acres of land. And nobody else in

10:21.014 --> 10:28.804
the family of Mr. Bruni knew about the acquisition 
of these 5,000 acres of land. But my father was so

10:28.824 --> 10:42.100
honest that after the funeral, he approached my 
father, approached the heirs, primarily Antonio

10:28.824 --> 10:42.100
Chico, as he used to refer to. And he told Antonio 
Chico, he said, listen, I have 5,000 acres that are

10:42.120 --> 10:50.110
under my name, but do not belong to me. I bought them 
with your father's money. And as soon as you have

10:55.383 --> 11:04.373
everything settled, let me know so that I can deed 
these 5,000 acres of land over to you and the

10:55.383 --> 11:04.373
family." And this is the type of honesty that he 
had. He just was very much what we sometimes refer

11:07.096 --> 11:14.604
to as a straight shooter. And it got to a point, 
especially later on, in actual documentation or

11:19.925 --> 11:47.974
knowledge for family trees and land titles that 
time and again my father was used to as a witness by

11:19.925 --> 11:47.974
both defense attorneys and counselors he was used 
as a key witness and none of the attorneys would

11:19.925 --> 11:47.974
ever challenge whatever he would say, you know, 
whenever he came, whenever he was put on the stand

11:48.342 --> 12:10.654
in land matters or land titles, neither party, 
neither party of either instance would ever

11:48.342 --> 12:10.654
challenge him because that's how well versed he 
was and that's how well respected the respect that

12:11.056 --> 12:18.630
he had from all of the attorneys, because they knew 
that whatever he would say was actually the actual

12:11.056 --> 12:18.630
truth. And through his testimony, there were many 
land titles that were settled and never

12:20.152 --> 12:31.613
challenged, primarily on his say-so, on his 
words. How did he happen to become involved with

12:32.420 --> 12:37.367
this Laredo law firm? Was there an incident that 
led to this? The incident that led to this was that

12:41.893 --> 12:57.195
his older brother, who used to have a creamery, 
used to have San Andres Dairy at the time. Which

12:57.293 --> 12:58.414
brother was this? This was a brother by the name of 
Serafin. Excuse me, not Serafin. It's an older

13:05.663 --> 13:07.085
brother. Adolfo, excuse me. Adolfo Martinez. And 
one early morning when he got up to milk the cows,

13:11.950 --> 13:22.643
and he stepped on a puddle. And while he was on the 
puddle, he went on to turn the light. So he got

13:26.531 --> 13:28.353
electrocuted. So my father, who was in Zapata at 
the time, came over and started doing some

13:29.835 --> 13:44.312
investigation work in order to bring his 
findings. And he used the law firm of Hicks, Hicks,

13:44.332 --> 13:47.736
Dixon, and Bobbitt. And the firm was so impressed 
in the manner that he conducted this

13:48.897 --> 14:09.895
investigation that Mr. Bobbitt, Judge Bobbitt, 
Robert Lee Bobbitt, as a matter of fact, and Yale

13:48.897 --> 14:09.895
Hicks, they offered him a position with the law 
firm. Of course, after that, he worked for 20 years

14:09.935 --> 14:14.579
with the law firm. And during this time, he was used 
to a great extent to investigate family trees and

14:18.901 --> 14:23.727
land titles. And it was during this time that he got 
to learn even more so about names, dates, places,

14:24.387 --> 14:32.457
family trees. And this, to him, was a school in 
itself, as he used to make reference. And after

14:41.948 --> 14:48.756
that, there were many people that thought that he 
was an attorney, which in fact he was not. But they

14:49.040 --> 14:54.970
would always come to him for all simple wills and 
deeds of trust. Well, he was a notary public. He was

14:56.372 --> 14:58.776
a notary public. But he definitely was not an 
attorney, even though many people still think

14:59.277 --> 15:04.786
that he was. But he did acquire this association in 
the mind of his friends and relatives. That's

15:11.918 --> 15:13.140
right. helped them, apparently, with quite a bit 
of legal work. To go back again to some of the early

15:18.862 --> 15:30.133
history, one of the questions that I had was about 
your father's first wife, not Guadalupe Uribe,

15:18.862 --> 15:30.133
his second wife. But the first- Maria Uribe, who 
was a sister of Guadalupe Uribe. They were both

15:37.300 --> 15:42.705
sisters, and they were first cousins of my father. 
And

15:42.938 --> 15:51.112
she died right immediately after childbirth. 
There was only one reference. There was one child,

15:52.795 --> 15:58.865
the baby, of course, that died a few weeks later. 
And then he married. How long had they been

16:02.472 --> 16:03.934
married? for a relatively short period of time. 
Short time. This was the first child. The very

16:07.977 --> 16:08.919
first child. Maria died. I would say probably just 
over a year at the most. Did he ever talk about that

16:12.244 --> 16:13.987
at all? Very little. He didn't write it into his 
papers either. No. And then he married this other

16:18.654 --> 16:24.222
sister who was the oldest in the family. She was 
several years older than he was. Quite a number of

16:27.007 --> 16:30.512
years older.

16:31.066 --> 16:35.373
He was married to her or lived for several years, 
quite a number of years. As a matter of fact, they

16:38.035 --> 16:46.244
They were the ones that moved over from Zapata 
County to Laredo and built the house on 416

16:38.035 --> 16:46.244
Lincoln. It was in the late 1920s. Do you live there 
now? That's where I presently live. At 416

16:52.771 --> 16:53.612
Lincoln. I just wondered. Yes, ma'am. So that's 
the mother house, you might say, or the father

16:56.956 --> 17:00.860
house. The father house. And after she died, then 
she married my mother. How did he meet your mother?

17:09.103 --> 17:29.878
Well, my mother came from Olzapata to work for my 
father because my father, well at the time, that

17:09.103 --> 17:29.878
my aunt Lupita was sick, she was extremely sick, so 
she came over to care for her. And after she died, my

17:30.736 --> 17:34.822
aunt Lupita. Your father's second wife. My 
father's second wife. Right, okay. And we call her

17:39.709 --> 17:43.114
Tia Lupita. But anyway, this is how the 
relationship started. And after she died, then a

17:48.642 --> 17:53.849
short while later, my father married my mother. 
Were they also kin? No. Well, probably they were

17:58.707 --> 18:04.996
kin, but there were quite a few distantly related. 
Quite a few degrees. In other words, practically

18:09.201 --> 18:17.512
everybody from San Ignacio and Guerrero all 
through there is connected in one way or another.

18:17.532 --> 18:18.173
One way or another. The relationship came from the 
Gutierrez family because my mother was a

18:18.654 --> 18:24.722
Gutierrez, so. That's where that relationship 
came from. And out of that union, only my sister and

18:30.662 --> 18:37.409
I were born. Now, your mother, Christina, had been 
married once before, had she not? She had also been

18:42.575 --> 18:44.617
married twice before. But she only had a child from 
one of those marriages. And so I have a

18:50.303 --> 18:53.106
half-sister. Where does she live? She's 
presently living in Corpus. While I'm thinking

18:58.507 --> 19:01.270
about it, where's Rosa living now? Rosa is living 
right across from where I live at 413 Lincoln

19:01.290 --> 19:06.776
Street. Has she married? No. No, she says that 
she's not about to support somebody.

19:15.526 --> 19:17.489
She's two years younger than I. At least her 
intentions right now are not too bad. What year

19:20.913 --> 19:22.114
were you born? I was born in 1937, July 25. You're 
exactly one year younger than I am.

19:31.730 --> 19:33.572
Is that right? All right. Well, let's see. There 
were several things that I particularly wanted to

19:36.035 --> 19:38.678
ask. Oh, while I'm thinking about it, I don't have 
the date of your father's death. When did he die

19:43.704 --> 19:46.988
exactly? I don't have it with me. And I'm afraid I 
cannot. Like I say, I'm not good at dates. But I'll

19:53.515 --> 19:57.180
find out, and I'll be more than happy to tell you 
about it. All right. What year was it? 1966. 1966. I

20:01.405 --> 20:03.588
wasn't sure of that either. But you can write me 
about it. Just 10 days before he was to complete his

20:07.793 --> 20:13.259
90th year. So he was 89 years old. 89, just 10 days 
shy of 90. 90 years old. This was in August. I'm

20:25.280 --> 20:28.565
afraid I can't, I don't recall the date. Well, the 
men in your family are notably long-lived. I'm

20:31.389 --> 20:34.754
afraid they are. Judge. The oldest, well, the 
latest one that died, let me put it this way, he died

20:35.155 --> 20:47.653
just about a little better than a year almost two 
years ago. And he was almost 98 years old when he

20:50.749 --> 20:55.635
died. Which one was that? Who was older? And that 
was one of your father's brothers? Brother, who

20:59.760 --> 21:01.421
was older than my father. So it's true. I mean, 
they're a strong fiber. You've got good genes for

21:08.430 --> 21:11.413
staying around a long time. Well, back to your 
father, after he retired from the law firm, one of

21:12.203 --> 21:23.724
the things he apparently did was work for the 
Boundary Commission. Could you tell me a little

21:24.646 --> 21:28.653
bit about the nature of his work with the Boundary 
Commission? Well, this was during the time that

21:28.954 --> 21:35.005
the International Boundary and Water Commission 
was going to build Lake Falcon. and they needed

21:36.183 --> 22:04.114
somebody that was well-versed with the families 
in the affected area that was well-versed with the

21:36.183 --> 22:04.114
titles land titles and also that was well-versed 
with the family trees within the area and because

21:36.183 --> 22:04.114
of that and of course by the fact that my father was 
already up in years he was already in his 70s They

22:04.769 --> 22:12.299
waived their requirement that they have to go 
through for civil service. And he was hired. And he

22:14.162 --> 22:22.013
conducted a considerable amount of 
investigation with regards to who should be paid

22:14.162 --> 22:22.013
and the amounts. And he was also the arbiter. He 
would come in as far as the settlement of many of the

22:25.577 --> 22:31.806
lands the different families and the different 
heirs. And through him, and primarily because of

22:37.070 --> 22:46.961
him, the greater part of all of that acreage was 
finally settled. Because he was a type that would

22:47.261 --> 22:57.793
devote a considerable amount of time to detail. 
And he was very meticulous and he would trace it all

22:58.246 --> 23:14.702
the way from the original grand tour in order to 
prove his point as to who was the original or the

22:58.246 --> 23:14.702
owner that should be paid or that settlement 
should be made. Well, in some cases, have these

23:15.138 --> 23:18.463
lands simply not been subdivided? That is 
correct. They were still being held in common by

23:19.704 --> 23:23.570
all the descendants? Exactly. And this is where my 
father's, I would say, invaluable knowledge came

23:24.271 --> 23:31.160
through. And there was a number of occasions I know 
that I myself personally would drive him to many of

23:31.180 --> 23:41.314
these old ranches where he would conduct personal 
interviews in order to clear a particular error or

23:41.767 --> 23:54.479
in order to find who the other issues were within 
the family. And in his reports, many times he

23:55.620 --> 24:05.549
provided family trees, which he would in turn turn 
over to the International Boundary Water

23:55.620 --> 24:05.549
Commission. So his help proved to be invaluable in 
trying to make final settlement for the Falcon.

24:15.761 --> 24:19.005
Now how did he feel about the Falcon situation? Do 
you remember? He believed in it because he felt

24:20.567 --> 24:30.201
that this would bring in a boom to the area which 
Let's face it, the agricultural economic area had

24:30.535 --> 24:43.634
been going down considerably, and he felt that the 
lake would provide particularly a tourist

24:30.535 --> 24:43.634
industry, which in effect it has. And 
consequently, this is one area that he believed

24:44.776 --> 24:48.140
quite strongly. The only one that he opposed, and 
he was able to oppose quite favorably, was the

24:48.781 --> 24:59.597
moving of San Ignacio.

24:59.898 --> 25:04.542
Again, primarily through his efforts, San 
Ignacio was left there. And I'm glad that it was,

25:05.383 --> 25:20.737
because all of the original houses, stone houses, 
like the old fort where they used to find Indians,

25:05.383 --> 25:20.737
and the original settlements, all of that 
definitely has been preserved. And he was the one

25:21.778 --> 25:29.905
that was initially contacted to get the 
International Boundary Water Commission and

25:30.745 --> 25:35.110
change its plans, which they did. Now, what was his 
particular reason for justifying the salvation

25:35.130 --> 25:40.417
of San Ignacio? Well, to a great extent, of course, 
he used the historical interest. And then he used

25:45.463 --> 26:00.702
the surveys that were done by the Boundary 
Commission as far as the altitude, which, let's

25:45.463 --> 26:00.702
face it, San Ignacio is in a much higher area, or the 
altitude there is much higher than the old Zapata.

26:01.103 --> 26:03.166
So it really wasn't going to be submerged. Not at 
all whatsoever. It has never been, not even in the

26:04.467 --> 26:15.762
latest flood, which was in 1954, and it was proven 
because it definitely did not reach San Ignacio. I

26:15.782 --> 26:21.289
mean, it was around it, but it didn't get at San 
Ignacio. So his point was well taken and well

26:21.309 --> 26:24.934
proven. Now, a lot was said. One of his very 
convincing arguments that he's left in his papers

26:28.124 --> 26:42.973
was that the terrible hardship that would be 
created by these people if they had to leave the

26:28.124 --> 26:42.973
homes of their ancestors and if they had to give up 
their lands that were along the river. Now, this,

26:45.797 --> 27:07.472
of course, was certainly very poignant, and he 
also pointed out that many of them might end up

26:45.797 --> 27:07.472
just, you know, going elsewhere, and maybe they 
couldn't even make a way for themselves, and he

26:45.797 --> 27:07.472
talked about their independence and this sort of 
thing, but to turn this around, this, of course,

26:45.797 --> 27:07.472
was true for San Ignacio, but what about the people 
of Old Zapata? Were they as socially disrupted as

27:10.797 --> 27:13.882
He argued the people of San Ignacio would have 
been. You must keep in mind that old Zapata had

27:13.982 --> 27:21.815
already been moved about two different times 
prior to that. So, in effect, we were not really

27:22.395 --> 27:26.402
talking about the original settlements. Because 
prior to that time, there used to be what they would

27:27.203 --> 27:34.054
refer to as the Carrizo. which was later changed to 
Zapata. And it was even further downriver. So in

27:39.578 --> 27:47.926
effect, we're not talking about a town that had the 
historical meaning that San Ignacio has. And

27:49.007 --> 27:59.738
true, there were some old stone houses there, but 
it definitely did not carry the historical

27:49.007 --> 27:59.738
background of San Ignacio. And to this extent, 
that's why we really did not carry the impetus or

28:00.072 --> 28:11.997
the catalyst or the influence that San Ignacio now 
definitely has. This is the main, main reason why.

28:14.990 --> 28:27.089
There was some talk at the time of putting, or at 
least some people in San Ignacio, excuse me, New

28:14.990 --> 28:27.089
Zapata, wanted to put two dams on the Rio Grande 
which would lower the level of the lake. Do you

28:27.149 --> 28:31.075
remember where your father stood on that 
particular issue? Because they were the two

28:31.139 --> 28:39.009
proposals, one to just keep the level, build a 
lower dam and another one upstream and save old

28:31.139 --> 28:39.009
Zapata too. Well, I'm afraid that I don't recall 
any comment from him along those lines. Well, that

28:43.795 --> 28:46.539
was rather, that was in the late 1940s. That was a 
